        <name>23.3.1.6 Task_2b</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Investigate the odd/even nature of sums and products of the following functions \(H(t)\) by calculating \(H(-t)\), expressing your answer in terms of the function \(H\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts_inline"&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;\(H(t) = h_1(t)h_2(t)\)
        &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
        where \(h_1(t)\) and \(h_2(t)\) are both even functions.
        &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
        \(H(-t) =\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]
        &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
        Therefore product of two even functions is an [[input:ans2]] function [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]
    &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;li&gt;\(H(t) = h_1(t) + h_2(t)\)
        &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
        where \(h_1(t)\) and \(h_2(t)\) are both even functions.
        &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
        \(H(-t) =\) [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]][[feedback:prt3]]
        &lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
        Therefore the sum of two even functions is an [[input:ans4]] function [[validation:ans4]][[feedback:prt4]]
    &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>We have 
\[ 
\begin{align}
H(t) &amp;amp;= h_1(t)h_2(t) \\
H(-t) &amp;amp;= (h_1(-t))(h_2(-t)) \\
&amp;amp;= h_1(t)h_2(t) \\
&amp;amp;= H(t)
\end{align}
\]
so the product of two even functions is &lt;b&gt;even&lt;/b&gt;.
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
Then, we have 
\[ 
\begin{align}
H(t) &amp;amp;= h_1(t) + h_2(t) \\
H(-t) &amp;amp;= h_1(-t) + h_2(-t) \\
&amp;amp;= h_1(t) + h_2(t) \\
&amp;amp;= H(t)
\end{align}
\]
so the sum of two odd functions is &lt;b&gt;even&lt;/b&gt;.</generalfeedback>
